        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">The fizzy beginnings</h2>  
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">If you were to Google the most popular beer in the world, the biggest beer brand, or even the top beer exporter, Heineken would pop up on nearly every list. Not just that. <strong>They've been consistently ranking among the top for over 140 years</strong>. So, how did this modest Dutch beer company end up clinking glasses around the globe? It’s a fizzy tale of bold vision, clever timing, and just a little carpe diem.
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/heineken-historic-delivery-trucks-amsterdam-brewery.png" alt="20th-century Heineken delivery trucks outside the original Heineken brewery in Amsterdam" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
         <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>20th-century Heineken delivery trucks outside the original Heineken brewery in Amsterdam. Credits: Heineken</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">It all began in 1864 when a young Gerard Adriaan Heineken bought “De Hooiberg,” a brewery in Amsterdam. <strong>In 1873, he officially founded the Heineken Bierbrouwerij Maatschappij</strong>. He hired Dr. H. Elion, a student of Louis Pasteur, to develop the famous <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-12-04-2025-heineken-a-yeast" target="_blank">Heineken A-Yeast</a>. They also became the <i>first brewer in the world</i> to introduce a quality control lab. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Two key accolades gave the brand credibility and helped it gain attention across Europe. In 1875, it bagged the <strong>Medaille d'Or at the International Maritime Exhibition</strong>, and in 1889, its crisp-tasting pilsner earned the prestigious <strong>Grand Prix at the Paris Expo</strong>. Just a year later, Heineken was being served at the restaurant in the Eiffel Tower, a clear signal that it had arrived as a premium, elite beer. 
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column> 
