          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">The green bottle effect
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">In 1933, rumors spread that the US might end the Prohibition era. Ever the opportunist, Heineken sensed that Americans would be craving a premium beer. <strong>They loaded a ship full of Heineken and sent it sailing to New York</strong>, making Heineken the first imported beer to hit American shores after the dry spell ended.
         </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Heineken also knew that image matters. Back then, American beer came mostly in brown bottles. <strong>Heineken’s green bottle stood out like a peacock at a pigeon party in a market full of brown bottles</strong>. The choice was intentional: it gave a premium, "imported" vibe that appealed to American drinkers. That bottle would become one of the brand’s most iconic trademarks. </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"><strong>While Gerard was the visionary who started Heineken beer, his grandson Freddy turned Heineken into the household name we know</strong>. When <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-12-04-2025-alfred-henry-freddie-heineken" target="_blank">Alfred Henry “Freddy” Heineken</a> stepped in, the Heineken family no longer owned the business, as his father, Henry Pierre, quietly sold the shares to meet the monetary obligations. Freddy bluffed his way into banks and pension funds, scraped together the necessary funds, and slowly bought back control. </p>
          </mj-text>
          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="#000000">
          <h2 style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            ">The Freddy factor</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5"><strong>One of Freddy’s boldest business moves came in 1968</strong> when he orchestrated a strategic merger with longtime rival and family nemesis Amstel. The timing wasn’t random. A challenger had entered the Dutch market: British brewing giant Allied Breweries, fresh from acquiring the massive Oranjeboom brewery in Rotterdam. Allied Breweries were preparing to turn Skol into Europe’s next big lager. By joining forces with Amstel, Freddy created a united Dutch front to counter the British invasion.</p>
          </mj-text>

          <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px 14px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/heineken-beer-bottle-evolution-display-history.png" alt="A display showcasing the historical evolution of Heineken's iconic beer bottle design" href="https://www.businesshistory.co" />
           <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
            <i>A display showcasing the historical evolution of Heineken's iconic beer bottle design. Credits: Heineken</i>
          </p>
        </mj-text>

          <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">In 1961, Freddy struck an agreement with Whitbread to sell Heineken in the UK. As demand boomed, by 1969, <strong>Whitbread began brewing a special, lighter version of the beer</strong> (a modest 3.2% ABV) to dodge Britain’s sky-high alcohol taxes. It wasn’t precisely the premium pour Freddy envisioned, but it sold in large numbers, thanks partly to <a 
style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #8C3321; color: black;" href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-12-04-2025-an-iconic-ad-campaign" target="_blank">an iconic ad campaign</a>. Featuring the tagline <i>“Heineken refreshes the parts other beers cannot reach,”</i> the campaign turned the watered-down version into a bestseller.</p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">Under Freddy’s leadership, Heineken went from a respected Dutch brewery to a true global giant. By the time he stepped down from the Executive Board in 1989, <strong>Heineken was being brewed or sold in over 200 countries, supported by a network of over 100 breweries</strong> worldwide. Heineken has brewed a global legacy, whether it’s the iconic green bottle, the mysterious A-Yeast®, or that crisp taste enjoyed on every continent.</p>
          </mj-text> 
